  "summaries": [
    {
      "id": "summary:abstract",
      "type": "abstract",
      "value": "Four anonymous Middle English tail-rhyme romances follow knights and families through combat, tournaments, exile, loss, courtship, pilgrimage, and reunion. Perceval moves from forest innocence into Arthurian knighthood; Isumbras undergoes divinely imposed poverty and penance before recovering his family; Eglamour completes deadly tasks and reunites with Cristabel and their son; Degrevant defends his estates, wins Melidor, and reconciles with her father.",
      "language": "eng",
      "scope": {
        "kind": "whole"
      },
      "evidence_ids": [
        "evidence:cme00026-xml",
        "evidence:dmer-romances"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "summary:contents",
      "type": "contents_note",
      "value": "The XML contains one title-page division and four complete poem divisions: Perceval, 143 verse groups and 2,288 encoded lines on printed pp. 1-87; Isumbras, 68 groups and 794 lines on pp. 88-120; Eglamour, 116 groups and 1,341 lines on pp. 121-176; and Degrevant, 119 groups and 1,906 lines on pp. 177-256.",
      "language": "eng",
      "scope": {
        "kind": "whole"
      },
      "evidence_ids": [
        "evidence:cme00026-xml",
        "evidence:xml-computation",
        "evidence:halliwell-1844"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "summary:scope",
      "type": "scope_note",
      "value": "The record describes Halliwell's encoded edition-level selection. Perceval and Isumbras derive from Lincoln MS 91; Eglamour from CUL Ff.2.38 with Lincoln variants; and Degrevant from CUL Ff.1.6 with Lincoln variants. Halliwell's unencoded apparatus establishes these dependencies but is not itself part of CME00026's selected text.",
